Dig. 42. 1.19. 1. This privilege was accorded by the law on three grounds. On account ol the peculiar personal relation between tbe parties it belonged to husband and wife against one another, to parents against children, patrons against freedmen (ξ 38 int), and to the father-inlaw ir sued by the husband sor a promised dos durante matrimonio. By reason ol the nature os the obligation upon which the action was based it was possessed by the husband and his representatives when sued sor the recovery ot a dos, by socii inter se, and by the promisor os a gift (ξ 38 int). On account of the personal position ol the debtor it belonged to the insolvent who had made a cessio bonorum (ξ 4ο int), to soldiers against all creditors whatsoever, and to children who had been recently released from patria potestas in respect ol debts contracted while alieni iuris, unless by the fathers death they had come into substantial property.
